{
  "Which of the following is a physical property?": "",
  "Reactivity with acid": "",
  "Flammability": "",
  "Combustibility": "",
  "Boiling point": "",
  "Boiling point can be observed or measured without changing the substance's chemical identity. Flammability, reactivity, and combustibility all require a chemical change to be observed.": "",
  "Which of the following is a chemical property?": "",
  "Color": "",
  "Melting point": "",
  "Density": "",
  "Flammability is a chemical property because it describes a substance's ability to burn (react with oxygen), forming new substances. Melting point, color, and density are all physical properties that can be observed without a chemical reaction.": "",
  "A physical property can be observed without:": "",
  "Touching the substance": "",
  "Changing the substance's chemical identity": "",
  "Looking at the substance": "",
  "Measuring it with instruments": "",
  "The defining feature of a physical property is that you can observe it without changing what the substance IS. Color, mass, volume, density, hardness, and boiling point can all be measured while the substance remains the same chemical.": "",
  "Reactivity with oxygen is classified as a:": "",
  "Intensive property": "",
  "Physical property": "",
  "Chemical property": "",
  "Extensive property": "",
  "Reactivity with oxygen describes how a substance chemically combines with O₂ — for example, iron rusting (Fe + O₂ → Fe₂O₃). Since it involves forming a new substance, it is a chemical property.": "",
  "Which is a physical property of iron?": "",
  "Silvery-gray color": "",
  "Burns in pure oxygen": "",
  "Rusts in moist air": "",
  "Reacts with acids": "",
  "Silvery-gray color is observed just by looking at iron — no chemical change needed. Reacting with acids, rusting, and burning all produce new substances (iron chloride, iron oxide), making them chemical properties.": "",
  "Malleability (being hammered into thin sheets) is a:": "",
  "Nuclear property": "",
  "Biological property": "",
  "Malleability describes a substance's ability to be hammered into sheets without breaking. This changes shape but not chemical identity, so it is a physical property. Metals like gold and copper are highly malleable.": "",
  "Which observation indicates a chemical property?": "",
  "Iron forms rust when exposed to moisture and air": "",
  "Ice melts at 0°C": "",
  "Sugar dissolves in water": "",
  "Glass shatters when dropped": "",
  "Rusting is a chemical change — iron reacts with oxygen and water to form iron oxide (rust), a new substance. Dissolving, melting, and shattering are physical changes that don't alter chemical identity.": "",
  "Conductivity — the ability to transfer heat or electricity — is what type of property?": "",
  "Reactive property": "",
  "Organic property": "",
  "Conductivity is measured by passing heat or electricity through a material — no chemical change occurs. Copper wire conducts electricity, but it remains copper before and after. Therefore, conductivity is a physical property.": "",
  "Toxicity — a substance's ability to cause harm to living organisms — is what type of property?": "",
  "Mechanical property": "",
  "Toxicity involves chemical reactions between the substance and biological systems (binding to enzymes, disrupting cellular processes). Because it depends on how the substance chemically interacts with the body, it is a chemical property.": "",
  "A student describes a substance: 'It is a shiny yellow solid that melts at 1064°C.' Which type of properties is she describing?": "",
  "Physical properties": "",
  "Both physical and chemical": "",
  "Chemical properties": "",
  "Neither — these are biological properties": "",
  "Color (shiny yellow), state (solid), and melting point (1064°C) can all be observed without changing the substance's identity. These are physical properties — and they happen to describe gold.": "",
  "What is the definition of a 'physical property'?": "",
  "A property that changes depending on how much substance you have": "",
  "A characteristic that can be observed or measured without changing the substance's chemical identity": "",
  "A property that requires a chemical reaction to be observed": "",
  "A property that only applies to solid matter": "",
  "Physical properties (color, density, melting point, hardness, conductivity, luster, solubility) describe the substance as it is — no new substance is formed during observation. The substance retains its chemical identity.": "",
  "What is the definition of a 'chemical property'?": "",
  "A property that describes appearance only": "",
  "A property that can be measured with a ruler or scale": "",
  "A property observed by changing temperature": "",
  "A characteristic that describes a substance's ability to undergo a change that produces one or more new substances": "",
  "Chemical properties describe what a substance CAN become — they can only be observed when the substance undergoes a chemical change. Examples: flammability, reactivity, oxidation potential, toxicity.": "",
  "What does 'flammability' mean?": "",
  "How quickly a substance melts when heated": "",
  "How brightly a substance reflects light": "",
  "The ability of a substance to burn in the presence of oxygen, producing heat and light": "",
  "The ability of a substance to conduct heat quickly": "",
  "Flammability is a chemical property measuring how easily a substance ignites and sustains combustion. Paper and gasoline are highly flammable; water and glass are not. Combustion is a chemical reaction: fuel + O₂ → CO₂ + H₂O + energy.": "",
  "What does 'ductility' mean?": "",
  "The ability of a substance to react with water": "",
  "The rate at which a substance dissolves in acid": "",
  "The ability of a substance to be drawn into thin wires without breaking": "",
  "The tendency of a substance to decompose over time": "",
  "Ductility is a physical property — it describes shape change, not chemical change. Copper and gold are highly ductile, which is why copper is used for electrical wiring. Brittle substances (like glass) are not ductile.": "",
  "What does 'luster' mean?": "",
  "How transparent a substance is": "",
  "A measure of how easily a substance breaks": "",
  "The color of light a substance emits when heated": "",
  "The way a substance's surface reflects light — described as metallic, glassy, waxy, or dull": "",
  "Luster is a physical property describing how light interacts with a surface. Metals typically have a shiny, metallic luster. Minerals are described as having glassy (quartz), waxy (jade), pearly, or dull luster.": "",
  "What does 'hardness' mean in chemistry?": "",
  "How quickly a substance burns, particularly regarding softest within the typical range of values": "",
  "A measure of how resistant a substance is to being scratched — ranked on the Mohs scale from 1 (talc) to 10 (diamond)": "",
  "How heavy a substance is per unit volume according to conventional analysis": "",
  "The ability to flex without breaking when evaluated systematically": "",
  "Hardness is a physical property measured by scratch resistance. The Mohs scale ranks minerals: talc (1) is softest, diamond (10) is hardest. A harder material can scratch a softer one. Glass (~5.5) can be scratched by quartz (7) but not by a fingernail (~2.5).": "",
  "What does 'reactivity' mean?": "",
  "How fast a substance moves through a tube": "",
  "The ability of a substance to change shape under pressure": "",
  "The tendency of a substance to undergo chemical reactions with other substances": "",
  "The color change that occurs when light hits a surface": "",
  "Reactivity is a chemical property that describes how readily a substance combines with or transforms other substances. Sodium is highly reactive (reacts explosively with water); gold has very low reactivity (resists corrosion).": "",
  "What does 'element' mean in chemistry?": "",
  "A pure substance consisting of only one type of atom, that cannot be broken down by chemical means": "",
  "A mixture of two or more different atoms": "",
  "A molecule with at least two different elements": "",
  "Any substance found in nature": "",
  "Elements are the simplest pure substances — made of one type of atom. There are 118 known elements on the periodic table. Gold (Au), oxygen (O), and carbon (C) are elements. They cannot be broken down into simpler substances by chemical reactions.": "",
  "What does 'compound' mean?": "",
  "Any substance that contains carbon": "",
  "A physical mixture that can be separated by filtration": "",
  "A pure substance made of two or more different elements chemically bonded in a fixed ratio": "",
  "A single type of atom found on the periodic table": "",
  "Compounds are formed when elements combine chemically in fixed proportions. Water (H₂O) is always 2 hydrogen to 1 oxygen. Unlike mixtures, compounds can only be separated by chemical means and have properties different from their component elements.": "",
  "What does 'pure substance' mean?": "",
  "A substance that exists only in nature": "",
  "A liquid with no dissolved particles": "",
  "Matter with a constant, definite composition — either an element or a compound": "",
  "Any substance that has been filtered": "",
  "A pure substance has a fixed composition. Elements (gold, oxygen) and compounds (water, NaCl) are pure substances. Mixtures are NOT pure substances because their composition can vary.": "",
  "A jeweler heats a metal sample to test it. The metal melts at 1,064°C, is shiny yellow, very malleable, and does not corrode or tarnish. She then dips it in strong acid — no reaction occurs. Which properties are physical, which are chemical, and what is the metal?": "",
  "Physical: melting point, color, malleability. Chemical: resistance to corrosion and acid. The metal is likely gold": "",
  "All properties listed are chemical — identification requires more data": "",
  "All properties listed are physical — the metal is copper": "",
  "Physical: acid resistance. Chemical: color and melting point. The metal is brass": "",
  "Melting point, color, and malleability are measured without creating new substances — physical properties. Resistance to corrosion and acid tests involve whether the substance reacts — chemical properties. Gold has all these characteristics: MP 1,064°C, yellow, malleable, and extremely low reactivity.": "",
  "A student lists the following about ethanol: 'clear, colorless liquid; boils at 78°C; density 0.789 g/mL; burns with a blue flame; mixes completely with water.' How many of these are physical properties and how many are chemical properties?": "",
  "2 physical and 3 chemical, particularly regarding into as predicted by standard models": "",
  "4 physical (appearance, boiling point, density, miscibility) and 1 chemical (flammability)": "",
  "3 physical and 2 chemical, particularly regarding colorless when": "",
  "All 5 are physical properties as typically measured in practice": "",
  "Clear/colorless (appearance), boiling point (78°C), density (0.789 g/mL), and miscibility (mixing with water) are all observed without changing ethanol into something else — physical properties. Burning (combustion) produces CO₂ and H₂O — that's a chemical reaction, so flammability is the chemical property.": "",
  "An antique bronze statue turns green over many years of outdoor exposure. A museum curator says, 'The green coating is called patina — it's copper carbonate formed when copper reacts with CO₂ and moisture.' Is patina formation a physical or chemical property?": "",
  "Physical property — no heat was involved, so no reaction occurred": "",
  "Neither — patina is just dirt accumulating on the surface": "",
  "Chemical property — copper reacts with carbon dioxide and water to form a new substance (copper carbonate)": "",
  "Physical property — the statue just changed color": "",
  "Patina formation involves a chemical reaction: copper reacts with CO₂, water vapor, and other atmospheric gases to form copper carbonate (CuCO₃) — a new substance with different properties (green color, different composition). The ability to form patina is a chemical property of copper.": "",
  "A forensic scientist tests two white powders. Powder A dissolves in water and has a salty taste. Powder B does not dissolve in water but reacts violently when vinegar (acid) is added, producing bubbles. Which property of Powder B helped most in identification?": "",
  "Insolubility in water (physical property) — this alone identifies the powder": "",
  "The violent reaction means it must be a dangerous explosive": "",
  "Reactivity with acid (chemical property) — the gas produced suggests it is a carbonate like baking soda": "",
  "White color (physical property) — most chemicals can be identified by color alone": "",
  "The bubbles when acid is added indicate a chemical reaction producing a gas (CO₂). This is a chemical property — reactivity with acid — and strongly suggests the powder is a carbonate (like baking soda, NaHCO₃). Physical properties like insolubility narrow options but don't uniquely identify it.": "",
  "A construction company needs to choose between wood and steel for a bridge in a coastal area with high humidity and salt spray. A chemist says, 'Consider both physical AND chemical properties.' What chemical property concern is most important for this decision?": "",
  "Density — lighter materials are always better for bridges": "",
  "Color — the bridge should match the landscape": "",
  "Hardness — steel is harder than wood, so it is automatically the better choice": "",
  "Reactivity with oxygen and moisture — steel corrodes (rusts) rapidly in salty, humid conditions": "",
  "Steel's tendency to rust (react with O₂ and H₂O to form iron oxide) is a critical chemical property for coastal construction. Salt accelerates this corrosion. Although steel is stronger (physical property), its chemical vulnerability may require expensive coatings or stainless steel alloys.": "",
  "A firefighter determines that a liquid spill at a factory is acetone (nail polish remover). She immediately keeps all ignition sources away, even though the liquid appears clear and harmless. Why is the chemical property of acetone more concerning than its physical properties?": "",
  "Acetone is highly flammable with a low flash point — it can ignite easily and cause an explosion or fire": "",
  "Clear liquids are always more dangerous than colored ones": "",
  "Acetone is extremely dense and could damage the floor": "",
  "Acetone has a very high boiling point, making it hard to clean up": "",
  "Acetone's flammability (flash point of -20°C) is a chemical property that poses immediate danger. Being clear and liquid are physical properties that seem harmless. In emergencies, chemical properties like flammability and toxicity often determine the response strategy.": "",
  "A geologist finds two minerals that both appear shiny and metallic. Mineral A scratches glass (hardness ~5.5) but not quartz (hardness 7). Mineral B scratches quartz easily. Which property is being tested, and what can be concluded?": "",
  "Flammability (chemical property) — scratching creates sparks": "",
  "Ductility (physical property) — the minerals are being stretched": "",
  "Reactivity (chemical property) — the minerals are reacting with the glass and quartz": "",
  "Hardness (physical property) — Mineral A has hardness between 5.5 and 7; Mineral B has hardness above 7": "",
  "The scratch test measures hardness — a physical property ranked on the Mohs scale. If Mineral A scratches glass (5.5) but not quartz (7), its hardness falls between 5.5 and 7 (possibly pyrite at ~6.5). Mineral B's hardness exceeds 7 (possibly topaz at 8 or corundum at 9).": "",
  "A chemistry teacher challenges students: 'Classify each as physical or chemical property — (1) copper conducts electricity; (2) sodium explodes in water; (3) mercury is a liquid at room temperature; (4) hydrogen peroxide decomposes into water and oxygen.' How many are chemical properties?": "",
  "4 — all involve changes, so all are chemical": "",
  "2 — sodium's explosive reaction with water and hydrogen peroxide's decomposition are chemical properties": "",
  "3 — all except mercury being liquid": "",
  "1 — only sodium's reaction with water is chemical": "",
  "(1) Conductivity — physical (no new substance). (2) Sodium + water → NaOH + H₂ — chemical (new substances formed). (3) Liquid state at room temperature — physical (no change in identity). (4) H₂O₂ → H₂O + O₂ — chemical (decomposition produces new substances). Two chemical properties total.": "",
  "An art restorer must identify whether a painting frame is solid gold or gold-plated copper. She cannot cut or damage the frame. Which combination of physical and chemical property tests could help without destruction?": "",
  "Weigh it — gold-plated items always weigh less": "",
  "Check if it conducts electricity — only gold conducts": "",
  "Heat it to its melting point to see if two layers separate": "",
  "Measure density (physical) and test a hidden spot with nitric acid (chemical) — gold doesn't react, copper does": "",
  "Density measurement (physical property) can reveal if the object is too light for pure gold (19.3 g/cm³ vs. copper's 8.96). An acid test on a tiny hidden spot (chemical property) is definitive: nitric acid dissolves copper (turns green) but does not react with gold. Both methods are minimally destructive.": "",
  "A pharmaceutical company discovers that a new drug is effective but decomposes rapidly when exposed to light and air. These stability issues are related to which type of properties, and how might the company address them?": "",
  "Physical properties — decomposition is just the drug dissolving": "",
  "Physical properties — store it at a colder temperature": "",
  "Chemical properties (photodegradation and oxidation) — address with opaque packaging and oxygen-free (inert gas) sealed containers": "",
  "Both — but nothing can be done about decomposition": "",
  "Decomposition by light (photodegradation) and air (oxidation) are chemical properties — the drug molecules break down into different substances. Using opaque containers blocks light, and sealing in inert gas (like nitrogen) prevents oxidation. Many medicines use amber bottles for exactly this reason.": ""
}